---
import LabLayout from "../../layouts/LabLayout.astro";

const title = "About | The AI Runtime Lab";
const description =
  "What an investigation is, and the lifecycle every investigation moves through, from question to field report.";

const lifecycle = [
  "Question",
  "Hypothesis",
  "Experiment",
  "Evaluation",
  "Reliability",
  "Production Trial",
  "Field Report",
];
---

<LabLayout title={title} description={description} ogType="article">
  <article class="lab-container about reading">
    <header class="about__head">
      <p class="mono-label" style="color: var(--accent)">About the Lab</p>
      <h1>An engineering notebook that became public.</h1>
    </header>

    <section aria-labelledby="what-heading">
      <h2 id="what-heading">What an investigation is</h2>
      <p>
        The Lab is the engineering arm of The AI Runtime. An investigation is
        Forward-Deployed Engineering done in the open: take a real
        customer-shaped problem, set a reliability bar, build the smallest
        system that can test it, and publish the failures, evals, decisions, and
        the final field report.
      </p>
      <p>
        Forward-Deployed Engineering means sitting with one customer's actual
        problem and shipping a system that holds a hard target under their real
        constraints: a fixed budget, messy public data, a precision floor that
        cold outreach depends on. That is the work here. These are not demos and
        not tutorials.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each investigation is built to be replicated. The reliability bar, the
        eval harness, the decision records, and the code are portable, so the
        next problem starts from a method, not a blank page. The point is a
        repeatable model for making AI reliable, not a one-off result.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="cadence-heading">
      <h2 id="cadence-heading">Updated weekly</h2>
      <p>
        Investigations are live records, not finished essays. Each one advances
        on a weekly cadence: a stage moves forward, a measurement lands, a
        decision gets recorded. The progress timeline on each investigation
        shows which of the stages below is done, in progress, or still ahead,
        and the investigation log captures what changed and when.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="lifecycle-heading">
      <h2 id="lifecycle-heading">The lifecycle</h2>
      <p>Every investigation moves through the same stages, in order:</p>
      <ol class="lifecycle">
        {lifecycle.map((stage, i) => (
          <li class="lifecycle__step">
            <span class="lifecycle__num">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
            <span class="lifecycle__label">{stage}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
      <p class="about__note">
        Each investigation also carries a status label for a quick read:
        <strong>investigating</strong>, <strong>in-eval</strong>, or
        <strong>published</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="more-heading">
      <h2 id="more-heading">More from The AI Runtime</h2>
      <p>
        The Lab is one arm of The AI Runtime, the community and publication for
        engineers shipping AI to production.
      </p>
      <ul class="links">
        <li><a href="https://theairuntime.com" rel="noopener">theairuntime.com</a>, the publication.</li>
        <li><a href="https://theairuntime.com/subscribe" rel="noopener">Subscribe to the newsletter</a> for new field reports.</li>
        <li><a href="/field-lab/">The Field Lab</a>, a library of production-shaped build problems.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</LabLayout>

<style>
  .about { padding: 3.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .about__head { margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
  .about__head h1 { margin-top: 0.8rem; }

  .lifecycle { list-style: none; margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: 0.4rem; }
  .lifecycle__step {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    background: var(--bg-2);
  }
  .lifecycle__num { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--accent); }
  .lifecycle__label { font-family: var(--font-mono); color: var(--text); letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
  .about__note { color: var(--text-2); }

  .links { padding-left: 1.2rem; }
  .links li { margin: 0.4em 0; }
</style>
